text: I'll tell you a funny story about factors and fundamentals. So we had invested once in a quantitative strategy, and it was ostensibly a quality strategy. It was using Petrovsky's F-score to screen out bad companies. And then based on what was left, it was using value to prioritize the names. And the value factors that it used differed across the market sectors. And so what the quantitative manager had done is he'd looked at the measures most commonly used by sell-side analysts for each industry sector, and he'd used those in his quant model. The measures used for the mining sector were different than the banking sector, etc. Now what ended up happening was, if you know how the Petrovsky model works, I'm sure you do, there's nine indicators in the score. A stock can have a score between zero and nine. But an eight isn't necessarily better than a seven or worse than a nine. The literature was sort of everything that was six and above was good, and everything that's six and below was not so good. So the measure was not necessarily monotonic in the way it worked. And this manager was applying it to Australian equities. And because of the structure of the market, the concentration of the market, you generally had larger, higher quality companies. So in terms of the top, 100 stocks, which is 80, 90% of the market cap, when we ran the analysis afterwards, we didn't realize this at first. All but two of them had a score above six. So the Petrovsky wasn't actually knocking anything out. So you were just left with the value. And then what happened with this value was the manager had realized after a while that he thought he wasn't backtesting or overfitting or having problems with his data by using the same data. And the investor thought, okay, it's really good, and then he began to try toag Hobby refining and then start getting out, doing his research piece on kind of trying to find out what the real value is for his Joe union custodians. They would say Arnold Jones got those top seven, only two under reviewing by any number of treasures. I mean, if it was the first chart took me to the last chart, I would probably be eliminate. Implicitly in thinking that he was trying to avoid data mining. He'd actually embedded it into his valuation measure so That was interesting and then talking to the manager at the time then they wanted to revise the model You know, they'd come out with a better version of Petrovsky It was sort of a Petrovsky plus and it had 20 things in it And so it was interesting watching that because that's probably a great example of quant gone wrong and what we learned from that So yeah, that was an interesting story
